\begin_layout Standard
Are errors really that important? In fact it is easy to imagine circumstances
 where the error or uncertainty of a measurement or prediction is at least
 as important as the central value itself.
 For example, suppose you work for 
\noun on
NASA
\noun default
 and you have discovered a rather large asteroid on a potential collision
 course with Earth.
 What do you do? Is it the time to ring up the President and the Hollywood
 action heroes? This dilemma crops up more often than you might think.
 Near Earth asteroids are being discovered faster than ever before (Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:nea-discovery-stats"

\end_inset

), and at the time of this writing there are 1484 space rocks in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

potentially hazardous asteroid
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (
\noun on
PHA
\noun default
) category 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PHAs"

\end_inset

.
 Yet, at present, there is no major threat from impacts.
 How is this so?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Astronomical measurements are only so good, and the positions and velocities
 of these objects are only determined within some uncertainty.
 Further, as they travel along their orbits are perturbed by the gravity
 of the planets and other forces which are harder to model (e.g., the 
\emph on
Yarkovsky effect
\emph default
).
 This means that the predicted position of the asteroid at some future time
 lies within some region of uncertainty.
 If the Earth is inside that volume then there is a potential, but uncertain,
 impact.
 A probability (a number between zero and one representing a degree of certainty
) can be assigned to the impact and this can be factored into the hazard
 as measured by, for example, the Palermo Technical Impact Hazard Scale
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PHAs"

\end_inset

.
 Only impacts which rate sufficiently highly on the scale merit attention
 by officials.
 Lower scoring impacts are likely to disappear as improved measurements
 reduce the uncertainty of the predicted orbit (Figure 
