\begin_layout Standard
I mentioned accuracy and precision before.
 These are different concepts.
 An ideal measurement has both accuracy and precision.
 A measurement is 
\emph on
accurate
\emph default
 if the average of many repetitions of the measurement tends to the true
 value as the number of repetitions increases.
 If the measurement is inaccurate then the average of repetitions will converge
 to some other value than the true value.
 A 
\emph on
precise
\emph default
 measurement is one that has nearly the same value on every repetition.
 A set of repetitions of an imprecise measurement shows a great deal of
 scatter.
 These qualities can be illustrated with a target analogy.
 In this analogy a measurement is represented by an arrow shot at a target,
 with the true value at the bullseye.
 A set of repetitions is shown in Figure 
