\begin_layout Standard
Inaccuracy and imprecision cause two different types of errors: systematic
 and random errors respectively.
 
\emph on
Random errors
\emph default
 or, equivalently, 
\emph on
statistical errors
\emph default
 are the result of uncontrollable random processes involved in the measurement.
 Examples include electrical noise, radioactive decays and reaction times
 (as in timing something with a stopwatch etc.).
 These errors benefit from averaging: when a measurement is repeated sometimes
 the random errors will produce a value larger than the true value, but
 other times they will produce a value smaller than the true value.
 Averaging together multiple repetitions washes out the individual fluctuations
 and produces a more certain estimate of the true value.
 The general rule of thumb is that the mean of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 independent repetitions of a measurement with an error of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

 has an error of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x/\sqrt{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Much more on this later.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Systematic errors
\emph default
 are those that affect all repetitions of a measurement equally and hence
 do not average out.
 They are the result of factors which could be corrected if they were known
 about, for example: miscalibrated measuring equipment, unaccounted for
 environmental effects, misalignments etc.
 Finding and eliminating systematic errors is essentially the craft of experimen
tal physics.
 An undiagnosed systematic error means you are not really measuring what
 you think you are, which can lead to potentially serious consequences.
 A parable and a modern day case study will amply illustrate the point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The parable tells of a man who wanted to measure the height of the emperor
 of China.
 So he travelled through China asking each person what they thought the
 height of the emperor was.
 We suppose they all know the height of the emperor to a precision of at
 least 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x=\pm1\ \mathrm{m}$
\end_inset

.
 If our researcher asks 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1\,000\,000\,000$
\end_inset

 people then the standard logic dictates that averaging their results gives
 an error in the mean of
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "JAYNESBOOK"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\Delta x}{\sqrt{n}}=3\times10^{-5}\ \mathrm{m}=0.03\ \mathrm{mm}!
\]

\end_inset

This result is clearly absurd.
 No one would call this a good way of measuring the height of the emperor
 of China.
 Surely most of the people polled have never even seen the emperor! However,
 a common folklore would have grown up around him as people told and discussed
 stories of their emperor
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This is common.
 To this day people persist in the illusion that Napoleon Bonaparte was
 short.
 He was average height for the time.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This measurement is thus a very precise measurement 
\emph on
of the folklore
\emph default
, but not of the actual height of the emperor.
 There is a systematic error propagated through the entire population which
 causes an illusion of the emperor distinct from the reality.
 The only way to obtain an accurate measurement of the emperor is to find
 the man himself and measure him.
 Of course, this is consistent with all common sense and probability theory.
 Only a failure to distinguish the different types of errors leads to the
 wrong interpretation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our case study is 
\noun on
OPERA
\noun default
: an experiment at the Gran Sasso Laboratory in Italy which measures a beam
 of neutrinos produced at the SPS proton accelerator at CERN in Geneva,
 730 km away (the beam goes through the ground: neutrinos are very weakly
 interacting particles, and pass through the Earth almost like it is not
 there).
 The neutrinos are produced in timed bunches.
 This set-up, with fixed source and target, allows a very accurate measurement
 of the travel time and hence the velocity of the neutrinos
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This is a small part of OPERA's research program.
 The velocity was originally considered a nice measurement they could do
 at no extra cost.
 It was not considered notable until the later controversy broke out.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 According to theory the velocity should be unmeasurably slower than the
 speed of light
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size normal
The velocity is 
\begin_inset Formula $v\approx c\left[1-\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{mc^{2}}{E}\right)^{2}+\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{m^{3}c^{6}}{E^{3}}\right)\right]$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is the neutrino mass, 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is the speed of light and 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is the neutrino energy.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $mc^{2}\sim1\ \mathrm{eV}$
\end_inset

 and OPERA has 
\begin_inset Formula $E\sim17\ \mathrm{GeV}$
\end_inset

, the neutrinos are expected to go at a fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim10^{-21}$
\end_inset

 slower than 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

, which is unmeasurably small.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and certainly not 
\emph on
more
\emph default
 than the speed of light.
 In other words the theory predicts that the measured value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(v-c\right)/c$
\end_inset

 should be consistent with zero.
 However, in 2011 OPERA reported a definitive measurement that the neutrinos
 travelled faster than light.
 They reported the result as follows: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(v-c\right)/c=\left(2.37\pm0.32\left(\mathrm{stat.}\right)_{-0.24}^{+0.34}\left(\mathrm{sys.}\right)\right)\times10^{-5}.
\]

\end_inset

There are a few things to notice here.
 They report the statistical uncertainty 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm0.32\left(\mathrm{stat.}\right)$
\end_inset

 and the systematic uncertainty 
\begin_inset Formula $_{-0.24}^{+0.34}\left(\mathrm{sys.}\right)$
\end_inset

 separately.
 Also, the systematic uncertainty has asymmetric error bars.
 The notation 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{-\Delta x_{2}}^{+\Delta x_{1}}$
\end_inset

 means the true value of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is likely between 
\begin_inset Formula $x-\Delta x_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x+\Delta x_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x_{1}=\Delta x_{2}$
\end_inset

 it is unnecessary to quote the two errors separately and you can use the
 more common notation for a symmetric error bar 
\begin_inset Formula $x\pm\Delta x$
\end_inset

.
 Also, note that they have pulled the common factor 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-5}$
\end_inset

 out of the whole central value and error bar expression.
 This makes the result easier to read.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-5}$
\end_inset

 multiplies every number inside the parenthesis.
 Finally, notice that the smallest possible value for 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 obtains if the statistical and systematic uncertainties are the most negative
 they can be: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\left(v-c\right)/c\right]_{\mathrm{minimum}}=\left(2.37-0.32-0.24\right)\times10^{-5}=1.81\times10^{-5}$
\end_inset

.
 Not only is this greater than zero, it differs from zero by more than five
 times the statistical uncertainty.
 This means that such a large disagreement is very unlikely to arise by
 chance.
 Thus OPERA confidently announced a 
\emph on
statistically significant
\emph default
 measurement of 
\begin_inset Formula $v>c$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two possibilities at this point: either not all sources of error
 were accounted for or the theory (Einstein's theory of special relativity)
 is wrong.
 While the media excitedly produced a torrent of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Einstein proved wrong
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 articles, the OPERA team set about the job of checking and re-checking
 everything that could possibly go wrong with their experiment.
 After months of work they were able to find two systematic errors that
 had not been accounted for: an incorrectly connected fibre optic cable
 and a drifting over time of the master clock.
 On fixing both these problems and re-running the experiment (with several
 other cross-checks) a revised measurement was obtained:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(v-c\right)/c=\left(2.7\pm3.1\left(\mathrm{stat.}\right)_{-3.3}^{+3.4}\left(\mathrm{sys.}\right)\right)\times10^{-6},
\]

\end_inset

which you can see is consistent with zero as theory predicted 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "OPERA"

\end_inset

.
 Since that time three other experiments have confirmed that neutrino velocities
 are compatible with the speed of light.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From a scientific perspective the provisional result and ensuing investigation
 and confirmatory experiments were handled correctly according to the scientific
 method.
 Unfortunately however, the press release led to a torrent of sensationalism
 in the media, which damaged the reputation of the OPERA team and lead to
 internal tensions, eventually resulting in several of the team leaders
 resigning from their leadership positions.
 There are two morals to the story: understanding and estimating the systematic
 uncertainties is crucial to the correct interpretation of an experiment;
 and hold carefully to the maxim 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

extraordinary claims require extraordinary evidence,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 especially when talking to the general public.
 The cost of a mistake can be your career.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are some other special types of errors worth mentioning.
 
\emph on
Digitisation error
\emph default
 is a random error that results from the limited precision of a decimal
 approximation to a real number.
 For example, suppose you are reading a digital voltmeter with the display
 format 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{XXX.XX}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the device can only display two digits after the decimal point the
 remaining digits of the true value must be rounded in some way.
 Different devices can do the rounding differently but you would generally
 expect 
\begin_inset Formula $0.004999\cdots$
\end_inset

 to round down and 
\begin_inset Formula $0.005000\cdots$
\end_inset

 to round up (this is by far the most common rounding method, but it is
 not universal).
 Assuming this is the rounding method then we know that a reading of 
\begin_inset Formula $123.45$
\end_inset

 volts corresponds to a true value between 
\begin_inset Formula $123.445$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $123.455$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we report the reading as the central value 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm$
\end_inset

 the difference between the central and the extremes
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
There is a case to be made for dividing the digitisation error by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{3}$
\end_inset

 before quoting it.
 This gives 
\begin_inset Formula $123.450\pm0.003$
\end_inset

 in the present case.
 The reasoning behind this will be discussed in the Advanced Topics section.
 For this course do not divide the error.
\end_layout

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $123.450\pm0.005$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Rounding error
\emph default
 is a related form of error when you round results at an intermediate stage
 of calculation.
 Rounding errors compound with each step of the calculation and numerical
 accuracy can be killed with surprisingly few stages of rounding.
 So take this advice: keep as many digits as possible in the intermediate
 stages of a computation, and only round off to a reasonable few at the
 final stage of reporting your results.
 Even better is to organise your calculations such that the minimum number
 of steps is required.
 For example, derive as many of the quantities of interest as possible as
 analytical formulae involving the things you immediately measure, and only
 substitute in the numerical values at the last stage.
 There are other tricks for organising your algebra.
 For example, if you need to compute a third order polynomial function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=a+bx+cx^{2}+dx^{3}$
\end_inset

 don't do it as written (which involves six multiplications and three additions).
 Instead rearrange the computation as 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=a+x\left(b+x\left(c+dx\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 which only involves three multiplications and three additions.
 Generally if the expressions have a lot of structure or repeating patterns
 they can be rearranged in some way to reduce the number of steps.
 Be especially careful if you need to take the difference of two large,
 close numbers to get a small number.
 For example, if you take 
\begin_inset Formula $12456-12453=3$
\end_inset

, but if you round prematurely you might get 
\begin_inset Formula $12460-12450=10$
\end_inset

 or even 
\begin_inset Formula $12500-12500=0$
\end_inset

! If you take basic precautions such as these, rounding error should be
 such a small part of your final uncertainties that we will not worry about
 how to estimate it.
