\begin_layout Itemize
A measurement without a quoted error bar is meaningless.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Much of the art of experimental physics is finding, estimating and controlling
 the various sources of error in an experiment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There are two general types of errors that concern us:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Random
\emph default
 or 
\emph on
statistical
\emph default
 errors are due to unpredictable and uncontrollable influences on the experiment.
 These errors can generally be reduced by averaging repetitions of the experimen
t, so long as enough time has passed between measurements for the random
 influences to have changed, but not so much time has passed that the thing
 to be measured has itself changed.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
A special case is digitisation error.
 The error is half of the last decimal place, e.g.
 if a digital measurement device reads 
\begin_inset Formula $123.45$
\end_inset

 then quote 
\begin_inset Formula $123.450\pm0.005$
\end_inset

.
 This is not strictly a random error, but for many purposes it can be treated
 as such.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Systematic
\emph default
 errors are due to regular but unaccounted for influences such as environmental
 conditions, miscalibrated equipment and improper measurement techniques
 (e.g.
 reading an analogue scale from an oblique angle).
 These can only be reduced by improving the experimental design.
\end_layout

