\begin_layout Subsection
Absolute and Relative Errors, Quoting of Errors
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Absolute-and-Relative-Errors"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So now that we have seen the importance of estimating errors and the different
 types of errors, how do you quote them? There are two basic ways.
 
\emph on
Absolute
\emph default
 errors are errors measured on an absolute scale in the same units as the
 measurement itself.
 For example, when measuring an electric current of 
\begin_inset Formula $250.0\ \mathrm{mA}$
\end_inset

 with a device that only shows tenths place there is a digitisation error
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $0.05\ \mathrm{mA}$
\end_inset

.
 This is in the same units as the thing we are measuring and is a characteristic
 of the measuring device independent of the scale of the thing being measured.
 It is an absolute error and we can report it as 
\begin_inset Formula $250.00\pm0.05\ \mathrm{mA}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the central value and the error are given in the same units and
 the unit is listed once at the end of the expression.
 Another common way of reporting the same value is 
\begin_inset Formula $250.00\left(5\right)\ \mathrm{mA}$
\end_inset

.
 The number in parenthesis indicates the uncertainty in the last digit.
 If the number in parenthesis had two digits it would represent the uncertainty
 in the last two digits, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $250.00\left(15\right)\ \mathrm{mA}$
\end_inset

 is the same as 
\begin_inset Formula $250.00\pm0.15\ \mathrm{mA}$
\end_inset

.
 You can use either notation so long as you are clear about the meaning
 of it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Relative
\emph default
 errors are the error reported as a fraction of the measured value.
 These gives a sense of how large the error is compared to the measurement
 itself, and are most often reported as percentages.
 In our case we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0.05\ \mathrm{mA}/250.00\ \mathrm{mA}=0.02\%,
\]

\end_inset

and we could quote 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(250.00\pm0.02\%\right)\ \mathrm{mA}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the relative error does not directly tell you much about the
 measuring device.
 For example, if the central value were ten times smaller the absolute digitisat
ion error would still be the same (assuming the meter does not change the
 display format as the scale changes), i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $25.00\pm0.05\ \mathrm{mA}$
\end_inset

.
 The relative error in this case is ten times larger, 
\begin_inset Formula $0.2\%$
\end_inset

.
 So relative errors are not as meaningful as absolute errors without also
 knowing the central value.
 However, relative errors are useful for many other purposes and are often
 a good way to quote the error.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now the matter of rounding.
 If you followed the advice of Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Precision-and-Accuracy-and-Types-of-Errors"

\end_inset

 and held off rounding intermediate results you will wind up with an end
 result something like 
\begin_inset Formula $123.45678901\pm0.00234567$
\end_inset

.
 I hope it is obvious that this has far too many figures.
 In practice you hardly ever know the uncertainty to better than two significant
 figures.
 In fact, you often only know the uncertainty to one significant figure.
 It is meaningless to quote digits of the central value that are a tiny
 fraction of the uncertainty: by the very definition of uncertainty you
 should have no confidence in these extra digits.
 So you should round your final results.
 Needless to say there is no universal standard for how to do this.
 For example, no less of an authority than the Particle Data Group offers
 this gem
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PDG2012"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation
The basic rules states that if the three highest order digits of the error
 lie between 100 and 354, we round to two significant digits.
 If they lie between 355 and 949, we round to one significant digit.
 Finally, if they lie between 950 and 999, we round up to 1000 and keep
 two significant digits.
 In all cases, the central value is given with a precision that matches
 that of the error.
 So, for example, the result (coming from an average) 
\begin_inset Formula $0.827\pm0.119$
\end_inset

 would appear as 
\begin_inset Formula $0.83\pm0.12$
\end_inset

, while 
\begin_inset Formula $0.827\pm0.367$
\end_inset

 would turn into 
\begin_inset Formula $0.8\pm0.4$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Don't do this! Life for a physics student is hard enough already without
 also having to cope with such a bizarre rounding rule.
 For the purpose of your undergraduate career you should round the error
 
\emph on
up
\emph default
 to two significant digits and round (standard rounding) the central value
 to a commensurate precision.
 So in the two examples above you should report 
\begin_inset Formula $0.83\pm0.12$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0.83\pm0.37$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 In my example you would quote 
\begin_inset Formula $123.4568\pm0.0024$
\end_inset

.
 Others will tell you to always round an error up to one significant figure
 (so, e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm0.22$
\end_inset

 becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm0.3$
\end_inset

), but sometimes this gets rid of too much information.
 For our purposes keeping two digits of the error is a fair compromise between
 being ultra-conservative keeping one digit and keeping meaningless extra
 digits, so long as you keep in mind that often the second digit of the
 error is itself fairly flexible.
 As I said, you almost never know more than two digits of the error, and
 often you only know one digit.
 If one of your instructors marks you down for keeping two digits of the
 error send them this document.
