\begin_layout Subsection
Linear Error Propagation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Linear-Error-Propagation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Often you can't directly measure the thing you are interested in.
 Instead you compute it as a function of quantities you can measure.
 But if you are uncertain about the value of some quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,z,\cdots$
\end_inset

, then obviously you will also be uncertain about the value of a function
 of them 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x,y,z\right)$
\end_inset

.
 How do you find out the uncertainty in 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

? You might imagine the simplest thing to do is to sample the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at many different values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,z$
\end_inset

 which are compatible with your measurements.
 This is in fact the Monte Carlo method that we will explore in Section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Advanced-Topics"

\end_inset

.
 It is a practical method if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is very complicated, or the number of variables is very large, or if their
 uncertainties are correlated
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
E.g.
 the uncertainties in the distance and intrinsic brightness of an astronomical
 object are correlated because objects which are further away will appear
 dimmer.
 Try thinking up your own examples.
\end_layout

\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is not a very smooth function of its arguments.
 The disadvantage is that you have to program a computer to do this for
 you, or otherwise do a lot of work
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
There are also modelling issues: you have to choose so called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

prior probability distributions
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

likelihood functions
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to do the estimation properly.
 There is an enormous literature on this subject which we only scratch the
 surface of in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Advanced-Topics"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Since we are often interested in simple functions of only a few variables
 we can use simple analytical rules to propagate uncertainties with pen
 and paper instead.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here is the general rule you will use for any undergrad subject:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta f\left(x_{0},y_{0},z_{0},\cdots\right)=\left|\frac{\partial f}{\partial x}\right|_{x=x_{0},\cdots}\Delta x+\left|\frac{\partial f}{\partial y}\right|_{x=x_{0},\cdots}\Delta y+\left|\frac{\partial f}{\partial z}\right|_{x=x_{0},\cdots}\Delta z+\cdots,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\right|$
\end_inset

 means absolute value and the subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $x=x_{0},\cdots$
\end_inset

 means to evaluate all the derivatives at the measured values 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0},y_{0},z_{0}\cdots$
\end_inset

.
 There is a term in the sum for each variable the function depends on.
 The absolute value sign is there so that each term contributes positively
 to the final result: increasing the uncertainty of any variable should
 always increase, and never decrease, the uncertainty of the function itself.
 An important point here is that the errors in the different variables must
 be uncorrelated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The justification for this rule is the Taylor series expansion for a function
 of several variables (we'll drop the 
\begin_inset Formula $z,\cdots$
\end_inset

 for brevity here, you can generalize this to any number of arguments):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f\left(x_{0}+\delta x,y_{0}+\delta y\right) & =f\left(x_{0},y_{0}\right)+\left.\frac{\partial f}{\partial x}\right|_{x=x_{0},\cdots}\delta x+\left.\frac{\partial f}{\partial y}\right|_{x=x_{0},\cdots}\delta y\\
 & +\frac{1}{2}\left.\frac{\partial^{2}f}{\partial x^{2}}\right|_{x=x_{0},\cdots}\delta x^{2}+\left.\frac{\partial^{2}f}{\partial x\partial y}\right|_{x=x_{0},\cdots}\delta x\delta y\\
 & +\frac{1}{2}\left.\frac{\partial^{2}f}{\partial y^{2}}\right|_{x=x_{0},\cdots}\delta y^{2}+\cdots,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

You can see the similarity.
 The main differences are that 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta x,\delta y,\cdots$
\end_inset

 can have any sign while 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x,\Delta y,\cdots$
\end_inset

 are always positive, so there are absolute value signs in the equation
 for the error; and that in the error formula we have dropped second and
 higher order terms in 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta x,\delta y$
\end_inset

.
 This is what we mean by 
\emph on
linear error propagation
\emph default
: we are essentially approximating a curved surface (the graph of the function
 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

) by a flat plane tangent to the surface at the measured point (c.f.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:uncertain-function"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This works so long as all the higher order terms are much smaller than the
 linear terms, e.g.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|\frac{\partial^{2}f}{\partial x^{2}}\right|_{x=x_{0},\cdots}\Delta x^{2}\ll\left|\frac{\partial f}{\partial x}\right|_{x=x_{0},\cdots}\Delta x,
\]

\end_inset

etc.
 (All higher order terms have to be much smaller than all linear terms.)
 This means the errors can't be too big:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta x\ll\frac{\left|\frac{\partial f}{\partial x}\right|_{x=x_{0},\cdots}}{\left|\frac{\partial^{2}f}{\partial x^{2}}\right|_{x=x_{0},\cdots}},\ \mathrm{etc.},
\]

\end_inset

which is usually the case.
 The most important case where linear error propagation fails is if the
 measured value happens to be near a 
\emph on
maximum, minimum,
\emph default
 or 
\emph on
inflection point
\emph default
 of the function.
 In that case linear error propagation 
\emph on
under-estimates
\emph default
 the error and you must use a non-linear error propagation technique which
 takes curvature of the function into account.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename images/uncertain-function.png
	width 90col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

