\begin_layout Standard
There is another, more subtle issue at work in our error propagation formula.
 It is not one you should worry about for your labs, but you should be aware
 of it.
 It is actually a fairly subtle, but crucially important point that was
 missed by many of the brightest minds for hundreds of years
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MOSTDANGEROUSEQ"

\end_inset

: in some cases our formula dramatically 
\emph on
over-estimates
\emph default
 the error.
 This is a concern especially when you are averaging multiple repetitions
 of a measurement to reduce the random error.
 Before getting there we will first use our general formula to derive some
 simple rules that will be very useful in practice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose our function consists of multiplication by an exact constant (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{circumference}=2\pi\times\mathrm{radius}$
\end_inset

 where the radius is being measured): 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=cx$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial f/\partial x=c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta f=c\Delta x$
\end_inset

.
 Convince yourself this should be obvious (you might think about unit conversion
s).
 What if we are adding two measured values together, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x,y\right)=x+y$
\end_inset

? Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial f/\partial x=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial f/\partial y=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Delta f=\Delta x+\Delta y$
\end_inset

.
 Again this should be fairly obvious.
 Here we can see what happens if variables are correlated.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is not really independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, but instead 
\begin_inset Formula $y=-x$
\end_inset

 exactly.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x,y\right)=x+y=0$
\end_inset

 exactly, no matter how uncertain we are in our measurement of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 But linear error propagation would say 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta f=\Delta x+\Delta y=2\Delta x$
\end_inset

 (remember 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x,\Delta y$
\end_inset

 are always positive!).
 So in the case of perfect (anti)correlation our formula over-estimates
 the error.
 These situations are fairly rare, and they can be handled on a case by
 case basis.
 This is not the problem I alluded to before, though it is closely related
 to it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Remember how I said that the error in an average of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 independent repeat observations with uncertainty 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x/\sqrt{N}$
\end_inset

? Let's see what the linear error propagation rule says:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset line
LatexCommand rule
offset "0ex"
width "100col%"
height "1pt"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Consider weighted averaging of repeated measurements 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\cdots,x_{N}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\left(x_{1},\cdots,x_{N}\right)=\sum_{i=1}^{N}w_{i}x_{i},
\]

\end_inset

where the weights obey
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{N}w_{i}=1,
\]

\end_inset

and the individual measurements have different errors 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 We would like to choose the weights so that the error of the average is
 as small as possible.
 Prove that using our linear error propagation rule the minimum 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta f$
\end_inset

 is always obtained for 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{\hat{i}}=1$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{i}$
\end_inset

 denotes the observation with the minimum uncertainty and all other 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{j}=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $j\neq\hat{i}$
\end_inset

.
 (Hint: you may start from this solution and show that no change to it can
 decrease the error.) Note that if the best two (or more) observations have
 the same error there is no unique solution for minimum error.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset line
LatexCommand rule
offset "0ex"
width "100col%"
height "1pt"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that the best strategy under linear error propagation is to take
 the single best observation and ignore all the rest.
 Not averaging! This is exactly what people did for many years before probabilit
y theory was better understood, but now it is known that averaging is actually
 better, and there is a subtle mistake in the linear error propagation formula.
 The problem is that there is still useful information contained in the
 less certain measurements that linear error propagation is leading us to
 throw away.
 Independent errors actually tend to wash each other out more so than our
 error formula suggests.
 This is especially important when a large number of samples are being averaged.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The completely general and correct method for updating our uncertainties
 in light of new information will be discussed in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Advanced-Topics"

\end_inset

.
 Here I will just quote the correct version of our error propagation formula
 (which we will call the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

quadrature
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 formula), still assuming uncorrelated and small errors, which should be
 reason enough to explain why I don't want you to worry about it except
 in the simple 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x/\sqrt{N}$
\end_inset

 case for averages:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta f\left(x_{0},y_{0},\cdots\right)=\sqrt{\left(\left|\frac{\partial f}{\partial x}\right|_{x=x_{0},\cdots}\Delta x\right)^{2}+\left(\left|\frac{\partial f}{\partial y}\right|_{x=x_{0},\cdots}\Delta y\right)^{2}+\cdots}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset line
LatexCommand rule
offset "0ex"
width "100col%"
height "1pt"

\end_inset


\end_layout

