\begin_layout Standard
How can we have two different rules for error propagation? The two rules
 are actually computing 
\emph on
two different things
\emph default
 that we have so far been using the same word for (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

error
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 A short exercise should illustrate what is going on:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset line
LatexCommand rule
offset "0ex"
width "100col%"
height "1pt"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Take 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x,y\right)=x+y$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $x=10\pm3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y=20\pm4$
\end_inset

.
 Compute 
\begin_inset Formula $f\pm\Delta f$
\end_inset

 using both linear error propagation and quadrature.
 Which is larger and by how much?
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
linear: 
\begin_inset Formula $30\pm7$
\end_inset

, quadrature: 
\begin_inset Formula $30\pm5$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset line
LatexCommand rule
offset "0ex"
width "100col%"
height "1pt"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is clear where the difference is coming from in this exercise.
 Linear error propagation is computing 
\emph on
the range over which 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 can vary
\emph default
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 consistent with the measured values.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 both err upwards then 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x+\Delta x,y+\Delta y\right)=\left(10+3\right)+\left(20+4\right)=30+7$
\end_inset

 and similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x-\Delta x,y-\Delta y\right)=30-7$
\end_inset

.
 So the range of possible 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 values is 
\begin_inset Formula $30\pm7$
\end_inset

 and this is exactly what you compute with linear error propagation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, quadrature is computing the 
\emph on
range of likely values of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset


\emph default
 (for some definition of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

likely
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that we will say much more about in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Advanced-Topics"

\end_inset

).
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are independent then upward fluctuations of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 are just as likely to occur with 
\emph on
downward
\emph default
 fluctuations of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and vice versa.
 So while 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
could be
\emph default
 as large as 
\begin_inset Formula $37$
\end_inset

 or small as 
\begin_inset Formula $23$
\end_inset

, it is 
\emph on
more likely
\emph default
 to be closer to 
\begin_inset Formula $30$
\end_inset

 than either extreme, since the fluctuations in 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 will often cancel out.
 We will see in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Advanced-Topics"

\end_inset

 not only how you can compute a summary statistic (
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta f$
\end_inset

) but also the actual 
\emph on
probability distribution
\emph default
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 (Needless to say, you will not need all this machinery for your lab reports,
 although if you read an experimental paper in astronomy or particle physics
 you are likely to see a great deal of this sort of probability analysis.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This issue is particularly acute in the case where you have many variables,
 such as an average.
 Suppose you are averaging 
\begin_inset Formula $1000$
\end_inset

 independent measurements.
 The chance of 
\emph on
all 
\begin_inset Formula $1000$
\end_inset

 of them
\emph default
 having a fluctuation in the same direction is minuscule.
 It is far more likely for roughly 
\begin_inset Formula $500$
\end_inset

 to fluctuate upwards, roughly 
\begin_inset Formula $500$
\end_inset

 to fluctuate downwards, and the errors are likely to wash out.
 The quadrature formula accounts for this.
 The linear error propagation formula does not: it tells you that, no matter
 how unlikely the event, 
\emph on
all
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $1000$
\end_inset

 measurements 
\emph on
could
\emph default
 fluctuate in the same direction yielding a much larger error estimate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that I have confused you with this long discussion of two distinct error
 propagation formulas, I will try to make up for it by giving a practical
 recipe.
 Now that you understand the general issue, and you are aware that the machinery
 discussed in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Advanced-Topics"

\end_inset

 automatically handles all cases correctly, in complete generality, you
 can understand that the simple recipe I give in this section is not iron
 clad.
 It is more of a useful rule of thumb that makes sure linear error propagation
 should cover most every case in your labs.
 Here it is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the function you are calculating involves no more than five (5) distinct
 variables, and you believe the errors are uncorrelated and relatively small
 (justifying a Taylor series expansion of the function) use linear error
 propagation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the function is an average of five or more independent measurements of
 the same thing then use quadrature (
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x/\sqrt{N}$
\end_inset

) for the average.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the function involves five or more distinct physical quantities, is highly
 nonlinear, or the errors are strongly correlated, your problem is probably
 complicated enough to need some special treatment using statistical methods.
\end_layout

